          <lg n="1">
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-1" n="1">Lean <hi rend="italics">Tom</hi>, when I saw him, last Week, on his Horse, awry,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-2" n="2">Threat'n'd loudly to turn me to Stone with his Sorcery.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-3" n="3">But I think, little <hi rend="italics">Dan</hi>, that in Spight of what our Foe says,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-4" n="4">He will find I read <hi rend="italics">Ovid</hi>, and his Metamorphoses.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-5" n="5">For omitting the first (where I make a Comparison,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-6" n="6">With a Sort of Allusion to <hi rend="italics">Putland</hi> or <hi rend="italics">Harrison</hi>,)</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-7" n="7">Yet by my Description, you'll find he in short is</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-8" n="8">A Pack and a Garran, a Top and a Tortoise.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-9" n="9">So I hope from henceÂ·forward you ne'er will ask, can I maul</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-10" n="10">This teazing, conceited, rude, insolent, Animal?</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-11" n="11">And, if this Rebuke might turn to his Benefit,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-X12-1101-line-12" n="12">(For I pity the Man) I should be then glad of it.</l>
          </lg>
        </div>
      </div>
